2.0.22
------

* **[P2]** `statechart_jobs.job_type` is now stored as a self-describing
  tagged literal (`pr-str`) and decoded via `edn/read-string` in
  `hydrate-job-row`. Consolidates encoding into the lib — prior to
  2.0.22, callers hand-rolled `(name src)` / `(subs (str src) 1)`
  to produce a bare-name string, which silently dropped namespaces on
  keys like `:my.app/x` (handler lookup then missed the registered
  handler). The new `job-type->str` / `str->job-type` mirror the
  existing `invokeid->str` / `str->invokeid` scheme: bare-unless-
  numeric keywords stay bare for back-compat, and anything else
  (strings, UUIDs, numbers, numeric-named keywords) carries a type
  marker so the decoder can reconstruct the original value. Legacy
  pre-2.0.22 rows decode via `:legacy-fallback :keyword`, preserving
  the existing `(keyword job-type)` semantics for rolling upgrades.
  The worker's handler lookup drops the `(keyword job-type)`
  coercion because `job-type` in a hydrated row is already the
  decoded keyword/symbol/UUID/number/string.

2.0.21
------

Seven correctness / robustness findings from the post-2.0.20 review.

* **[P1]** Fallback event-ACK no longer fires when the handler's
  save-working-memory! call rolled back. Since 2.0.16 the JDBC event
  queue installs `::sc/on-save-hooks` so the event ACK commits atomically
  with the WM save; after the handler returns it ALSO ran a separate
  unconditional `mark-processed!` as a fallback ACK for handlers that
  never called save (terminated / missing session). That fallback had
  no visibility into whether a save was attempted: a handler that
  called `save-working-memory!`, had the tx roll back (OCC conflict,
  constraint violation, connection loss), caught the exception, and
  returned normally would still be ACKed by the fallback — silently
  losing the event. The new contract threads an `::sc/save-attempted?`
  atom through env that `save-working-memory!` flips before opening its
  tx; the fallback fires only when the atom is still `false`. Both
  shapes are pinned: `receive-events-does-not-silently-ack-when-save-
  rolls-back-test` (new) closes the hole; `receive-events-fallback-ack-
  still-fires-when-no-save-attempted-test` protects the
  terminated-session path the fallback exists for.

* **[P1]** `StatechartInvocationProcessor/start-invocation!` now blocks
  on the async child save instead of leaking an unresolved
  `Promise<true>` to the caller. Previously `(p/then result save!)` on
  the async path returned a pending promise that resolved when the
  child's WM save committed — but the SCXML processor calling
  `start-invocation!` would proceed to save the parent's own WM (and
  therefore ACK the parent event via the on-save hook) before the
  chained save resolved. If the child save then rejected (DB error,
  OCC), the parent event was already ACKed, the child was never
  persisted, and the next poll couldn't retry. `start-invocation!`
  now `@`-derefs the chained promise so it always returns a boolean
  and the child is durable by the time control returns to the
  processor. Regression:
  `statechart-invocation-async-child-save-completes-before-return-test`.

* **[P1]** `release-terminal-dispatch-claim!` is guarded against
  accidental clears of unclaimed rows. The UPDATE previously matched
  `WHERE id = ?` with no state guard; the docstring rationalised this
  as "the caller owns the claim by construction," but a stray
  release (double-call from racing catch blocks, or wrong job-id) would
  silently rewrite `terminal_event_dispatched_at` to nil on an
  unrelated row. New WHERE clause adds `AND terminal_event_dispatched_at
  IS NOT NULL`, making the release a 0-row no-op on unclaimed rows
  and idempotent for double-release. Regression:
  `release-terminal-dispatch-claim-only-affects-claimed-rows-test`.

* **[P1]** `JdbcWorkingMemoryStore/delete-working-memory!` now purges
  queued events for the deleted session in the same tx as the session
  DELETE and the job cancellation. Previously pending rows in
  `statechart_events` with `target_session_id = <deleted-session>`
  lingered until a worker claimed them, ran the handler against a
  missing WM, and eventually cleared them via the fallback ACK — waste
  of worker cycles and a contradiction of the atomic-cleanup promise
  in the docstring. Three writes now commit atomically:
  `cancel-by-session-in-tx!`, `DELETE FROM statechart_events WHERE
  target_session_id = ? AND processed_at IS NULL`, and the session
  row DELETE. Regression:
  `delete-working-memory-purges-pending-events-test`.

* **[P1 / best-effort]** `event_queue/claim-events!` unfiltered path
  now excludes sessions that already have an in-flight claim by any
  worker, via a `NOT EXISTS` subquery. The function's docstring
  claimed per-session FIFO within a batch; cross-worker FIFO was
  silently broken — worker A claiming event 1 for session S did not
  prevent worker B from claiming event 2 for S in the same instant.
  The guard closes the common window. It is **not a global lock**:
  two workers racing on the exact same instant can both see the
  session as un-claimed and both win the `FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED`
  lottery. Callers who need strict ordering should partition workers
  by `:session-id` (already supported) or run a single worker;
  docstrings updated to say so explicitly. The session-filtered claim
  path omits the guard so a session-scoped worker can continue to
  make progress on its own session. Regression:
  `claim-skips-sessions-with-in-flight-claims-test`.

* **[P2]** `StatechartInvocationProcessor/start-invocation!`
  hook-stripping is now pattern-based, not a single-key denylist.
  Previously only `::sc/on-save-hooks` was dissoced and a code comment
  warned future maintainers to add each new hook keyword. The new
  `strip-parent-hooks` sweeps every `::sc/*-hooks` key (plus the event
  queue's `::sc/save-attempted?` signal) in one pass, so a future
  hook is automatically excluded from child env without a manual
  update. Regression:
  `statechart-invocation-strips-all-sc-hooks-keys-from-child-env-test`
  covers the hypothetical `::sc/on-delete-hooks` and `::sc/pre-save-
  hooks` keys.

* **[P2]** `working_memory_store/fetch-session` no longer crashes on a
  malformed `statechart_src` row. Previously `edn/read-string` was
  called without try/catch, so a corrupted or partially-written row
  threw and that session became permanently unreadable. The decode
  now falls back to the raw string with an error log so callers can
  surface the corruption rather than silently wedge. Regression:
  `fetch-session-survives-corrupted-statechart-src-test`.

Also in this release:

* **Partial index** `idx_events_unclaimed_deliver ON statechart_events
  (deliver_at, id) WHERE processed_at IS NULL AND claimed_at IS NULL`
  supports the unfiltered `claim-events!` path directly, replacing the
  previous index-backward scan on `idx_events_target_deliver`.

* **Lease expiry is server-side.** `claim-jobs!` and `heartbeat!` now
  compute `lease_expires_at = now() + interval` in SQL rather than
  application-side (`OffsetDateTime/now + Duration/ofSeconds`). App
  clock skew against the DB server no longer stretches or compresses
  the lease window.

* **`cancel-events!`** logs at DEBUG when its DELETE affected zero
  rows — SCXML permits the race between "cancel a delayed event" and
  "event delivery," but the silence was misleading. The log lets
  operators correlate a "cancelled" event with its subsequent
  delivery.

* **`pg-env`'s `:node-id`** docstring now explicitly requires global
  uniqueness across worker processes and recommends a
  `<hostname>-<pid>-<random-uuid>` shape for operator-supplied values.

* **`affected-row-count`** no longer checks the legacy pg2-era
  `:updated` / `:deleted` / `:inserted` keys. `next.jdbc` produces
  only `:next.jdbc/update-count`, so the branches were dead and
  misleading anyone reading the function for "what shapes might I
  receive."

* **Property-based round-trip tests** over `[:or uuid? number?
   keyword? string?]` cover all three encode/decode pairs
  (session-id, event-queue invoke-id, durable-job invoke-id) with 200
  examples per property. The CHANGELOG since 2.0.13 kept patching
  newly-discovered `::sc/id` subtypes one case at a time; a generator
  now fails before the subtype slips through.

* **Shared test fixtures** extracted into
  `persistence.jdbc.fixtures` (test-config, with-pool, with-clean-
  tables). Previously the same block was copy-pasted across four
  files; a PG-config change needed four edits.

2.0.20
------

Close the critical regression introduced by 2.0.19's claim-before-dispatch
rewrite, plus the four follow-up recommendations on 2.0.19.

* **[P1 — fixes 2.0.19 regression]** Terminal-event dispatch checks
  session readiness BEFORE claiming the dispatch slot. 2.0.19 moved the
  claim in front of the send to eliminate duplicate dispatch, but the
  pre-existing `dispatch-terminal-event!` returned `false` without
  sending whenever `get-session-state-fn` indicated the parent wasn't
  yet ready (a normal retry condition — parents routinely start
  observing an invocation only after the child has begun). Under 2.0.19
  the claim committed anyway in that path, marking the row dispatched
  even though no event had been enqueued, and the reconciler never
  picked it up again → terminal event permanently lost, parent stuck.
  The fix splits `dispatch-terminal-event!` into a pure
  `session-ready-for-dispatch?` check plus a pure `send-terminal-event!`
  call, and composes them as `claim-and-send-terminal-event!`:

      (if-not (session-ready-for-dispatch? exec-opts job)     ; no side effects
        false
        (if-not (job-store/claim-terminal-dispatch! pool id)  ; atomic claim
          false
          (try
            (send-terminal-event! …)
            true
            (catch Exception e
              (job-store/release-terminal-dispatch-claim! pool id)  ; roll back
              (throw e)))))

  Not-ready rows stay un-claimed for the next reconciliation pass.
  Send failures roll back the claim. Duplicate dispatch across
  concurrent callers remains impossible (claim is atomic). All four
  call sites (execute-job! success, execute-job! fail,
  execute-claimed-job! unhandled-type, reconcile-undispatched!) go
  through the single composite helper. Regressions:
  `reconcile-not-ready-session-keeps-job-retryable-test`,
  `worker-terminal-send-includes-invoke-id-test` and
  `session-ready-for-dispatch-treats-nil-as-not-ready-test`
  (both renamed from their pre-split names).

* **Nested `core/with-tx` is forbidden in this codebase.** 2.0.19's
  `delete-session!` wrapped `cancel-by-session!` + the session DELETE
  in an outer `with-tx`, then let `cancel-by-session!` open its own
  inner `with-tx`. `next.jdbc/with-transaction`'s default
  `:nested-tx :commit` commits the inner body's writes regardless of
  what happens in the outer block — so a failing outer DELETE left
  every pending job cancelled but the session row intact, which is the
  exact atomicity property we thought we were ensuring. `:nested-tx
  :ignore` would have hidden the issue; `:savepoint` is untested in
  this codebase; neither is appropriate. Fix: `cancel-by-session!` is
  split into `cancel-by-session-in-tx!` (takes an open Connection, no
  `with-tx`) and the public `cancel-by-session!` (opens its own tx and
  calls the `-in-tx` helper). `delete-session!` calls the `-in-tx`
  variant directly so cancellation participates in its own outer
  transaction. `core/with-tx`'s docstring now states that nesting is
  forbidden and points to the `-in-tx` pattern for helpers that need
  to cooperate with a caller's open transaction. Regression:
  `delete-working-memory-rolls-back-job-cancellation-on-failure-test`.

* **Async invocation path covered by test.** 2.0.19's hook-stripping
  fix preserves the `(dissoc env ::sc/on-save-hooks)` in the
  `p/then` continuation by closure capture, but there was no test
  exercising a promise-returning `sp/start!`. Added
  `statechart-invocation-async-path-strips-parent-ack-hooks-test`.

* **Comments pointing out future hazards.** `start-invocation!`'s
  hook-stripping site now notes that any future env-carried
  side-effect hook (e.g. `::sc/on-delete-hooks`) must be added to the
  dissoc. `delete-session!` calls out that it calls
  `cancel-by-session-in-tx!` rather than `cancel-by-session!`
  specifically because nested `with-tx` is forbidden.

2.0.19
------

Four runtime-correctness findings from the post-2.0.18 review.

* **[P1]** `StatechartInvocationProcessor` strips the parent's
  `::sc/on-save-hooks` from env before starting a child chart. The
  JDBC event queue injects a hook so the parent event is ACKed
  atomically with the parent's WM save. 2.0.16 routed `start-invocation!`
  through that same env — so entering a `:statechart` invoke marked
  the parent event processed as soon as the CHILD session saved, BEFORE
  the parent actually saved. A later parent save failure (optimistic
  lock conflict, DB error) released the claim but the row already had
  `processed_at` set, silently losing the parent event while the child
  chart had been started. Fix: `(dissoc env ::sc/on-save-hooks)` in
  the path that saves the child's WM. Regression:
  `statechart-invocation-strips-parent-ack-hooks-from-child-save-test`.

* **[P1]** `JdbcWorkingMemoryStore/delete-working-memory!` now cancels
  any durable jobs the session owns, in the same transaction that
  drops the `statechart_sessions` row. Previously only the session
  row was deleted. When
  `StatechartInvocationProcessor/stop-invocation!` triggers session
  deletion on invoke exit, active `:durable-job` rows stayed pending
  / running: workers kept executing side effects for a session that
  no longer existed, and later emitted `done.invoke.*` /
  `error.invoke.*` events that had nowhere valid to go. The tx
  wraps `job-store/cancel-by-session!` + the session row delete so
  either both commit or neither does. Cancellation writes
  `terminal_event_name` on each row so the reconciler can still
  dispatch `error.invoke.<invokeid>` to any chart that was observing.
  Regression: `delete-working-memory-cancels-durable-jobs-test`.

* **[P1]** `FlatWorkingMemoryDataModel` reads the pre-9330ee6 legacy
  data-model key for restart-recovery and rolling-upgrade compat.
  Commit 9330ee6 (2026-01-11) moved the flat model's storage key from
  the namespace-local `::wmdm/data-model` to `::sc/data-model`. Working
  memory persisted before that commit holds its map under the old key;
  after upgrade, `current-data` returned `nil` and `update!` started a
  fresh map, so any JDBC-persisted session looked blank until recreated.
  Since `pg-env` uses the flat model by default, this broke rolling
  upgrades and restart recovery for existing deployments. `current-data`
  now returns the merge of legacy-key and new-key data (new wins on
  collision); `update!` reads from that same merged view and, on the
  first write, dissocs the legacy key so repeated reads/updates don't
  resurrect data that was subsequently deleted. Regression:
  `flat-data-model-reads-legacy-data-model-key-test`.

* **[P2]** Terminal job dispatch is now atomically claimed so
  concurrent reconcilers cannot duplicate-dispatch. The previous flow
  was plain SELECT → `send!` → `mark-terminal-event-dispatched!`;
  two reconciler passes (across workers, or after a crash between
  `send!` and the mark) could observe the same row and enqueue the
  same `done.invoke.*` / `error.invoke.*` twice. Because
  `get-session-state-fn` is optional and the parent may not have
  consumed the first event yet, duplicates drove double transitions.
  New `job-store/claim-terminal-dispatch!` is a conditional
  `UPDATE ... WHERE terminal_event_dispatched_at IS NULL` that returns
  `true` for the first caller and `false` for everyone else. The
  reconciler and all three `execute-job!` terminal paths (success,
  handler failure, no-handler failure) now claim before `send!`.
  Trade-off: a crash between the claim commit and the event-queue
  `send!` commit now loses the terminal event (previously that same
  crash produced a duplicate). Single-event loss is auditable —
  rows with `terminal_event_dispatched_at` set but no corresponding
  row in `statechart_events`. Duplicate dispatch drove divergent
  parent state and was the greater harm. Regression:
  `claim-terminal-dispatch-is-atomic-test`.

2.0.18
------

Close the five review recommendations on 2.0.17. Shipped together
since each addresses a gap in the same consolidation refactor.

* **Decoder gating closes two behaviour changes introduced by 2.0.17.**
  The unified `decode-id` ran its `#`-tagged-literal branch and
  `parse-uuid` step for every call site regardless of the legacy data
  each site needed to remain compatible with. Both are now gated on
  `:legacy-fallback`:
  - `:string` (session-id) enables `parse-uuid` (pre-2.0.11 wrote
    UUIDs bare) but disables `#`-read (pre-2.0.11 session-id writers
    never produced `#` forms; a bare string starting with `#` is raw
    user content, not a tagged literal). So a pre-2.0.11 session-id
    row `\"#{1 2 3}\"` stays a string instead of decoding as a set,
    and `\"#uuid \\\"…\\\"\"` stays a string instead of decoding as a
    UUID.
  - `:keyword` (invoke-id) enables `#`-read (post-2.0.4 / post-2.0.8
    invoke-id writers use `pr-str` for UUIDs and produce `#uuid \"…\"`
    on disk) but disables `parse-uuid` (pre-2.0.4 / pre-2.0.8 bare
    invoke-id rows were written via `(name x)` which only accepts
    keywords/strings, so a UUID-shaped bare row represents a keyword
    whose name happened to be UUID-shaped — not a UUID).
  Regressions: `decode-id-preserves-session-id-legacy-behavior-test`,
  `decode-id-preserves-invoke-id-legacy-behavior-test`,
  `decode-id-option-matrix-test`.

* **`encode-id` nil handling is explicit.** 2.0.17 dropped the old
  `session-id->str`'s `:else (str session-id)` branch, so passing `nil`
  stopped matching any `cond` arm and silently returned `nil` (cond
  default) for session-ids but `(pr-str nil)` = `\"nil\"` for invoke-ids
  once the invoke-id encoder was also routed through `encode-id`. Both
  are wrong in different ways. `encode-id` now wraps its body in
  `(when x ...)` and documents the behaviour: `nil` in, `nil` out.
  This surfaces the caller bug at the `NOT NULL` session-id column
  rather than silently writing `\"\"` (pre-2.0.17 session-id) or `\"nil\"`
  (2.0.17 transitional). Regression: `encode-id-option-matrix-test`
  nil case.

* **`encode-id` has an explicit `:else` fallback** to `pr-str`. This is
  only reachable for invalid (non-`::sc/id`) input and matches the
  pre-2.0.17 invoke-id encoder's behaviour. Previously the lack of an
  `:else` in the cond meant non-`::sc/id` input silently returned `nil`,
  which propagates to an unexpected SQL NULL downstream.

* **Public API stability notes** on `encode-id`, `decode-id`, and
  `tagged-number-re`. All three remain public and documented as stable
  since 2.0.17 — option sets may grow (with backwards-compatible
  defaults) but will not shrink.

* **Direct unit tests** for the `encode-id` / `decode-id` option
  matrix. The three subsystem wrappers cover the three in-use
  configurations indirectly; the new tests exercise each option flag
  in isolation so a future caller using an unusual combination has
  documentation of the intended behaviour.

* **In-code comment** in `decode-id`'s `:else` explaining that the
  parser order (`parse-long` → `parse-double` → gated `parse-uuid` →
  `tagged-number-re` + EDN → legacy-fallback) is load-bearing — none
  of the earlier parsers would correctly classify inputs the later
  ones handle, and reordering would silently change type choices.

2.0.17
------

Consolidate the three parallel `::sc/id` encode/decode sites into a
single implementation. Pure refactor — no behavioural change, no new
coverage, nothing on disk moves.

`core.clj` now owns `encode-id` and `decode-id` (plus the shared
`tagged-number-re` and `numeric-bare-name?` helpers). Each call site
is a thin options-carrying wrapper:

- `core/session-id->str` / `str->session-id` — sessions. Options pin
  `:uuid-shape :bare` (pre-2.0.11 compat), `:keyword-shape :marked`,
  `:legacy-fallback :string` on decode.
- `event_queue/parse-invoke-id` — queued events. `:legacy-fallback
  :keyword` on decode; writer is already `pr-str` in `event->row` so
  it maps to `:uuid-shape :tagged, :keyword-shape :marked` on encode.
- `job_store/invokeid->str` / `str->invokeid` — durable jobs.
  `:uuid-shape :tagged, :keyword-shape :bare-unless-numeric,
  :symbol-shape :bare-unless-numeric` (pre-2.0.8 compat);
  `:legacy-fallback :keyword` on decode.

Incidental, not a behaviour change for any real deployment: the
unified decoder now includes the `#`-tagged-literal branch and
`parse-uuid` on every call site. Previously `job_store/str->invokeid`
lacked `parse-uuid`, and `str->session-id` lacked `#`. Neither was
reachable in practice (`job_store` always wrote UUIDs with `#uuid`
so bare UUIDs never appeared; `session-id->str` never wrote `#`
forms) but the asymmetry was confusing.

Motivation: the five patch releases between 2.0.12 and 2.0.16 each
fixed one of these encoders in isolation and left the others behind.
New `::sc/id` edge cases (ratios, bigints, scientific bigdecimals,
tagged-numeric keywords, collision-adjacent shapes) kept slipping
through whichever site had been patched least recently. With a single
implementation, a future fix in one place covers all three subsystems.

Also fixes framing in the 2.0.16 entry:

- The atomic-ACK [P1] was framed as a regression; in fact the split
  transaction has existed since the JDBC backend landed in cb8f2f2
  (v2.0.0). 2.0.12 only added the promise-await step; it did not
  create the crash window. The 2.0.16 fix closes a pre-existing gap,
  not a recent regression.
- The tagged-numeric invoke-id [P2] items were framed as regressions
  too. They are better read as incomplete fixes: v2.0.4 and v2.0.8
  rewrote the invoke-id encoders to handle broader types but the
  accompanying decoders never caught up to BigInt / BigDecimal /
  Ratio. 2.0.16 finished what those releases started.
- The explicit `:child-session-id` [P1] item was correctly framed
  as a regression — 7d018d7 (2026-02-02) introduced unconditional
  scoping that overrode user-specified session ids.

2.0.16
------

Four correctness findings from the post-2.0.15 review.

* **[P1]** Event ACK is atomic with working-memory persistence.
  Previously `receive-events!` marked a row processed in a separate
  transaction after the handler returned, and the handler's
  `save-working-memory!` had already committed in its own transaction.
  A crash, DB error, or connection loss between the WM save and the ACK
  left WM advanced but the event unacked — stale-claim recovery then
  re-delivered it against already-advanced state, running
  non-idempotent actions twice (direct "exactly-once" violation).
  `JdbcWorkingMemoryStore/save-working-memory!` now reads
  `::sc/on-save-hooks` from env and runs them inside its own
  transaction. The JDBC event queue injects a `mark-processed!` hook so
  the ACK commits atomically with the save. A separate post-handler
  `mark-processed!` is kept as an idempotent fallback for handlers that
  succeed without calling `save-working-memory!` (e.g. terminated /
  missing session). Regression:
  `save-working-memory-runs-on-save-hooks-test`.

* **[P1]** `StatechartInvocationProcessor` preserves explicit
  `:child-session-id`. 7d018d7 unconditionally rewrote every child
  session to `<parent>.<invokeid>`. That was correct for
  auto-generated invokeids (collision avoidance) but regressed the
  documented `:child-session-id` routing option — a route configured
  with `:child-session-id "admin"` no longer created a child session
  at `"admin"`, so `scf/send!`, URL sync, and child restoration all
  stopped finding the child. The algorithm now threads
  `:explicit-id?` through `start-invocation!`, `stop-invocation!`, and
  `forward-event!`; when true, the processor uses the invokeid as the
  session-id directly (matching the pre-7d018d7 documented behavior
  and the `elements.cljc` docstring on `invoke`). Auto-generated
  invokeids remain scoped. `stop-invocation!` and `forward-event!`
  also probe the WM store for both scoped and bare forms to cover
  legacy callers that don't yet thread `:explicit-id?` through.
  Regression:
  `statechart-invocation-preserves-explicit-session-id-test`.
  `invocation/statechart-spec.cljc` updated to assert the new
  (correct) explicit-id behavior — the old scoped assertion was
  codifying the bug.

* **[P2]** Tagged numeric invoke-ids in queued events now decode back
  as numbers, not keywords. `event->row` persists `:invoke-id` via
  `pr-str`, so `42N`, `3.14M`, `1/2` were stored as tagged numeric
  literals. The old `parse-invoke-id` only EDN-read plain integers and
  decimals; tagged forms fell through to `(keyword s)`, surfacing as
  `:42N` / `:1/2` in the handler. `handle-external-invocations!`
  matches by `=` against the original idlocation value, so queued
  terminal events silently skipped finalize/autoforward for those
  ids. `parse-invoke-id` now has the same tagged-number regex gate as
  `core/str->session-id`. Regression:
  `parse-invoke-id-accepts-tagged-numeric-literals-test`.

* **[P2]** Tagged numeric invoke-ids in durable-job hydration now
  decode back as numbers, not keywords. Same class of bug as above,
  on a different code path: `invokeid->str` wrote non-keyword
  invoke-ids via `pr-str`, but `str->invokeid` only reconstructed
  UUIDs, quoted strings, and plain longs/doubles. A durable job
  started with invokeid `42N` / `3.14M` / `1/2` hydrated back as
  `:42N` / …, so the worker dispatched `done.invoke.*` /
  `error.invoke.*` with the wrong id and the parent never saw the
  completion event. `str->invokeid` now has the same regex-gated
  EDN-read branch. Regression:
  `str-invokeid-accepts-tagged-numeric-literals-test`.

2.0.15
------

Review follow-ups on 2.0.14.

* **[P3]** `tagged-number-re` now accepts scientific-notation
  BigDecimals (`1E+10M`, `9.99E+50M`, `1.5E-10M`, …). Clojure's
  `pr-str` produces `E+` / `E-` forms for BigDecimals outside a narrow
  magnitude window, so the 2.0.14 regex silently failed to round-trip
  any BigDecimal whose magnitude pushed it into scientific notation
  (roughly `|x| >= 1e7` or very small unscaled values). Regex is now
  `#"-?\d+(\.\d+)?([Ee][+-]?\d+)?[NM]|-?\d+/-?\d+"`. Regression:
  scientific-notation cases added to `number-subtypes-round-trip-test`.

* **Migration note (missing from 2.0.14)** — pre-2.0.14 BigInt session
  ids were written via `session-id->str`'s old `:else` branch, i.e.
  `(str 42N) = "42"` (no `N` marker). Starting at 2.0.14, those legacy
  bare-`"42"` rows decode as `Long 42` rather than `BigInt 42N`. This
  is the same type of silent narrowing that 2.0.13's CHANGELOG flagged
  for digit-only string session-ids; it was just never called out for
  the BigInt case. Users with BigInt session-ids pre-2.0.14 will see
  their type narrow to Long on read. Re-save to restore BigInt
  identity. Pinning test: legacy-bigint case in
  `number-subtypes-round-trip-test`.

* Defensive pinning tests added so that future refactors fail loudly:
  `re-matches` → `re-find` regression would silently accept trailing
  junk like `"42Nabc"` → now covered; `resolve-invocation-session-id`
  tier-3 requiring `state-map` in an `and` refactor would break
  callers who pass `nil` state-map → now covered; new `fulcro-api-spec`
  behavior pins tier-3 with nil state-map.

* Docstring: `resolve-invocation-session-id` tier 3 now explicitly
  states it fires regardless of `state-map` (the previous doc implied
  state-map presence was relevant).

2.0.14
------

Review follow-ups on 2.0.13.

* **[P3]** `session-id->str` / `str->session-id` now preserve every
  `number?` subtype (`Long`, `Double`, `BigInt`, `BigDecimal`, `Ratio`)
  rather than just `Long` / `Double`. `::sc/id` is
  `[:or uuid? number? keyword? string?]`, so all of these are
  legitimate session-id shapes. `session-id->str` now writes numbers
  via `pr-str`, which keeps the `N` / `M` / ratio tags; plain
  `Long` / `Double` still serialize to the same bare form as 2.0.13.
  `str->session-id` adds a gated `edn/read-string` branch for
  `<digits>N` / `<digits>.<digits>M` / `<int>/<int>` shapes. The regex
  gate keeps legacy bare strings like `"my-session"` from accidentally
  parsing as symbols. Regression: `number-subtypes-round-trip-test`
  plus new `core-spec` cases.

* Cleanup: removed the dead `(symbol? session-id)` branch in
  `session-id->str`. `::sc/id` does not permit symbols, and the branch
  was semantically identical to the `:else` `(str x)` fallback (since
  `pr-str` of a symbol does not add a marker, unlike for keywords or
  strings). Updated `core-spec` to pin the new behavior: symbols go
  through `:else` and do not round-trip.

* Docstring fixes: `session-id->str` doc no longer claims symbols
  keep a marker (they never did). `str->session-id` doc now mentions
  the 2.0.13 migration note in-place (legacy pre-2.0.11 digit-only
  strings decode as numbers). `integration.fulcro/resolve-invocation-
  session-id` doc now describes all four resolution tiers — the
  previous doc omitted the "scoped-id as best-guess fallback" arm.

2.0.13
------

Two correctness findings from the post-2.0.12 review.

* **[P1]** JDBC session-id serialization preserves numeric
  session-ids. SCXML `::sc/id` permits numbers; `session-id->str`
  already wrote them as bare strings (`(str n)`), but
  `str->session-id` had no branch for them — it returned a bare string
  like `"42"`. Subsequent saves then went through the string `pr-str`
  path and wrote `"\"42\""`, so the row written under `"42"` never got
  read again and event delivery silently stopped. `str->session-id`
  now tries `parse-long` / `parse-double` before `parse-uuid` in the
  bare-string branch. Strings must be written via `pr-str` (quoted)
  to survive round-tripping, which has been the stored shape since
  2.0.11. Regression: `numeric-session-id-round-trip-test` plus
  updates to `core-spec` covering numeric round-trip and the
  legacy-bare-digits → number tradeoff. Migration note: legacy
  pre-2.0.11 rows that stored a *string* session-id whose contents
  happened to be digit-only (e.g. `"12345"`) will now decode as the
  number `12345`. Post-2.0.11 rows are unaffected because strings are
  stored with the `pr-str` marker.

* **[P2]** `integration.fulcro/resolve-invocation-session-id` prefers
  the fork's scoped child session (`<parent-session-id>.<invokeid>`)
  over a top-level session whose id collides with the raw
  `stored-id`. Previously the `cond` checked `stored-id` first, so a
  pre-existing top-level session with the same name as the invokeid
  would shadow the real scoped child — cross-chart routing and
  invocation event-forwarding would send events to the wrong session.
  Now the scoped child wins whenever it exists in `state-map`.
  Regression: `resolve-invocation-session-id` specification in
  `fulcro-api-spec` with an explicit collision case.

2.0.12
------

Four correctness findings from the post-2.0.11 review.

* **[P1]** `receive-events!` now awaits the handler's promise before
  `mark-processed!` / `release-claim!`. Paired with the async processor
  (or any promise-returning handler), 2.0.11 ACKed the row before the
  handler actually finished — later events for the same session ran
  against stale working memory, and a rejected/crashed promise lost the
  event. Synchronous handlers are unaffected (non-promise return → no
  wait). Regression:
  `receive-events-awaits-async-handler-promise-test`.

* **[P2]** `session-id->str` / `str->session-id` round-trip correctly
  for string session-ids that look like UUIDs or keywords. Strings are
  now stored with a quoted pr-str form; the decoder shape-inspects
  (leading `"` → string, leading `:` → keyword, else UUID-or-legacy
  bare). Legacy bare rows still decode correctly. Regression:
  `session-id-roundtrip-preserves-type-test`.

* **[P2]** `parse-event-type` handles quoted string types (e.g. the
  SCXML transport URI `\"http://www.w3.org/tr/scxml\"`) — previously
  these round-tripped as the keyword `:"http://…"` because only
  leading-`:` shapes were EDN-read. Regression:
  `event-queue-string-type-roundtrips-as-string-test`.

* **[P2]** `dispatch-terminal-event!` treats a nil session-state
  result as "not ready". Previously `if-let` fell through to the
  "no checker installed" branch and dispatched unconditionally — the
  guard was ineffective in exactly the cases it was meant to protect
  (parent session gone or stale). Regression:
  `dispatch-terminal-event-treats-nil-session-state-as-not-ready-test`.

Tests `core-spec` / `core-test` updated to pin the new session-id
write format (quoted string); round-trip assertions unchanged.

2.0.11
------

Cleanup follow-ups from the post-2.0.10 review.

* **[P2]** `statechart_definitions` DDL is no longer created. The 2.0.10
  deletion of `JdbcStatechartRegistry` left the schema, drop, and
  truncate paths still touching the table. `create-tables!` no longer
  produces it; `drop-tables!` still drops it (kept as a migration aid
  for pre-2.0.10 deployments); `truncate-tables!` no longer names it.
  README chart-definitions section removed. Regression test:
  `create-tables-does-not-create-definitions-table-test`.

* **[P3]** `invocation/future` cancellation detection now walks the
  cause chain. A body that catches `InterruptedException` internally
  and rethrows a wrapping exception (common pattern with
  `ExecutionException` / `CompletionException` / domain wrappers) used
  to misclassify cancellation as a real invocation failure. Also
  restores the thread interrupt flag via
  `(.interrupt (Thread/currentThread))` when we swallow the interrupt —
  standard Java convention. Regression test:
  `future-cancellation-with-wrapped-interrupt-is-suppressed-test`.

* Nit: `pg-env` now asserts `(satisfies? sp/Processor processor)` at
  construction so misconfiguration fails fast rather than blowing up
  the first time a chart tries to run. Regression covered by extending
  `pg-env-accepts-custom-processor-test`.

2.0.10
------

Three findings from the post-2.0.9 review.

* **[P1]** `invocation/future` no longer reports cancellation as an
  invocation error. `stop-invocation!` cancels the future via
  `future-cancel`, which interrupts the thread — blocking operations
  inside the body surface `InterruptedException` / `CancellationException`.
  The `catch Throwable` branch previously treated these as failures and
  emitted an `:error.invoke.*` event back to the parent, driving
  transitions that should never fire after the state was already left.
  The catch now suppresses the send for interrupt/cancel exceptions and
  logs a debug line instead. Regression test:
  `future-cancellation-does-not-emit-error-invoke-test`.

* **[P2]** `pg-env` accepts a caller-supplied `:processor`. Previously
  the sync `v20150901` processor was installed unconditionally, so
  consumers pairing an async execution model (`lambda-async`, or any
  model returning Promesa promises) with `pg-env` got their guards and
  actions evaluated by the sync algorithm — unresolved promises were
  treated as truthy values. New option overrides the default.
  Regression test: `pg-env-accepts-custom-processor-test`.

* **[P2]** `JdbcStatechartRegistry` is deleted. It used `nippy/freeze`
  on the whole chart definition, which throws `Unfreezable type` for
  any realistic chart because guards / actions / invoke `:src` values
  are closures. `pg-env` has used the in-memory `local-memory-registry`
  since 2.0.0 specifically to sidestep this. Consumers calling
  `new-registry` from `persistence.jdbc.registry` directly will now get
  a namespace-not-found error at load time instead of a cryptic runtime
  `Unfreezable` exception the first time they register a non-trivial
  chart. `pg-env`'s `::sc/statechart-registry` is unchanged.

2.0.9
-----

Three more findings from the post-2.0.8 review.

* **[P1]** `cancel-by-session!` is atomic again. 2.0.8's switch from a
  single SQL UPDATE to SELECT + per-row UPDATE dropped atomicity — a
  mid-loop DB error could leave a session partially cancelled. The
  SELECT and every UPDATE now run inside a single `with-tx`, so
  cancellation is all-or-nothing. Regression test:
  `cancel-by-session-atomic-on-midway-failure-test`.

* **[P2]** Digit-starting keyword invokeids (`:42`, `:3.14`, `:-dashy`)
  now round-trip to their original keyword instead of being decoded as
  numbers. `invokeid->str` detects names that would parse as a number
  and stores them via `pr-str` (with the leading `:`) so the decoder
  can disambiguate. Extended `invokeid-roundtrip-preserves-all-
  supported-types-test`.

* **[P2]** `event_queue/parse-invoke-id` and `job_store/str->invokeid`
  now agree on the type of legacy bare-string rows: both return
  keywords. Pre-2.0.4 / pre-2.0.8 rows were always keyword-typed (the
  old write paths only accepted keyword/string/symbol and keywords were
  the dominant case), so keyword is the correct guess for bare form.
  `handle-external-invocations!`'s `=` match now works uniformly
  regardless of which decoder the chart goes through. Regression test:
  `event-queue-legacy-bare-invoke-id-decodes-as-keyword-test`. The
  obsoleted 2.0.5 `legacy-invoke-id-decodes-as-string-test` is removed.

2.0.8
-----

Closes the remaining durable-job invoke-id correctness gap:
`str->invokeid` used to always coerce to a keyword, so a durable job
started with a string / UUID / number invoke-id round-tripped back as
`:report` / `:abc-…` / `:42` (keywords). The worker then emitted
`done.invoke.*` / `error.invoke.*` with the keyword in `:invoke-id`,
and `handle-external-invocations!` (which matches by `=` against the
original idlocation value) missed finalize/autoforward bookkeeping.

Fix pair:

* **`invokeid->str`** now uses `pr-str` for non-keyword/non-symbol
  values — `\"report\"` → `\"\\\"report\\\"\"`, UUIDs → `\"#uuid \\\"…\\\"\"`,
  numbers → `\"42\"`. The leading marker lets the decoder distinguish
  them from bare-keyword legacy rows. Keywords/symbols still serialize
  bare, so existing keyword rows stay readable.
* **`str->invokeid`** now shape-inspects:
  - strings starting with `\"` or `#` → `edn/read-string`,
  - all-digits-with-optional-decimal → `parse-long` / `parse-double`,
  - everything else → `(keyword s)` (legacy/bare keyword form).

* **`cancel!`** now builds the terminal event name via
  `(pr-str (evts/invoke-error-event invokeid))` instead of
  string-concatenating the bare invokeid string (which only worked for
  keyword invokeids).
* **`cancel-by-session!`** switched from one SQL-concat UPDATE to a
  SELECT + per-row UPDATE loop so the terminal event name can be
  constructed in Clojure for each typed invokeid.

Regression test:
`invokeid-roundtrip-preserves-all-supported-types-test` — covers
`:kw`, `:my-ns/kw`, `\"report\"`, `\"looks-like-a/ns\"`, `42`, `3.14`,
and a UUID.

2.0.7
-----

Follow-up from the post-2.0.6 review.

* **Revert a silent breaking change introduced in 2.0.6**: the qualified-
  keyword branch of `durable-job/invoke-data-keys` remapped the
  data-model key shape (e.g. `:my-ns/my-invoke` → `:my-ns.my-invoke/job-id`
  instead of the pre-2.0.6 `:my-invoke/job-id`). Charts that read their
  durable-job data-model keys via guards/actions/RAD integration would
  have silently stopped finding the stored job-id. Restored to
  `(name invokeid)` for both simple and qualified keywords. The
  UUID/number crash fix (the original #H) is preserved — strings/UUIDs/
  numbers still fall through to `(str invokeid)`.

* **Perf polish**: `datasource-closed?` now memoizes its per-class
  `getMethod("isClosed")` lookup instead of reflecting on every event
  loop iteration.

* **Docs**: `README.md` updated to show the 2.0.6 idiom of adopting
  `(:env loop-handle)` for `send!` so events auto-wake the loop.

Regression coverage:
* `invoke-data-keys-qualified-keyword-shape-unchanged-test` — pins the
  pre-2.0.6 key shape.
* `future-invocation-done-event-includes-invoke-id-test` — pins the done
  path that 2.0.6 also fixed (error was the only one flagged in review).

2.0.6
-----

Five more correctness fixes. Regression tests in `regression_test.clj`
findings #G–#K.

* **[P1]** `job_store/invokeid->str` no longer strips the first character
  of non-keyword invoke-ids. `(subs (str invokeid) 1)` was only correct
  for keywords; for string/UUID/number invoke-ids (all valid `::sc/id`
  shapes reachable via `idlocation`), it corrupted storage (`"report"` →
  `"eport"`, `42` → `"2"`). Workers built `done.invoke.*` /
  `error.invoke.*` from the corrupted string, and parents never saw
  their terminal event. Now branches on type — keywords unchanged,
  others use plain `str`.
* **[P2]** `durable-job/invoke-data-keys` no longer throws on UUID/
  number invoke-ids. `(name x)` only accepts keyword/string/symbol;
  previous code crashed AFTER `create-job!` had inserted a pending row,
  leaving orphaned jobs in `statechart_jobs`. Now dispatches on type and
  flattens qualified keywords to a dotted form.
* **[P2]** `invocation/future` now includes `:invoke-id` on both the
  done and error sends. `handle-external-invocations!` matches terminal
  events to `<invoke>` elements by `:invokeid`, so finalize content and
  autoforward were skipped on the failure path.
* **[P2]** `start-event-loop!` now returns `:env` alongside `:stop!` /
  `:wake!`. Callers who want `send!` to auto-wake the loop must use this
  env — previously `env-with-signal` was trapped inside the closure, so
  `send!` on the caller's original env saw `::wake-signal=nil` and new
  events waited the full `poll-interval-ms`.
* **[P1]** `datasource-closed?` no longer treats a single failed
  `getConnection` call as permanent closure. The 2.0.2 fallback probe
  couldn't distinguish transient outages from shutdown; a transient DB
  blip on a non-Hikari DataSource flipped `running=false` and stopped
  the event loop forever. Now only `isClosed()` signals closure;
  DataSources without that method return `false`, and operators call
  `(:stop! loop-handle)` explicitly on shutdown.

2.0.5
-----

* Fix a backwards-compatibility regression introduced in 2.0.4's `:invoke-id`
  decoder: `(try (edn/read-string s) (catch Exception _ s))` coerced legacy
  bare-string rows (e.g. `"my-invoke"` written by pre-2.0.4 code via
  `(name invoke-id)`) to **symbols** rather than the strings pre-2.0.4 code
  returned, because `edn/read-string` of a bare token yields a symbol without
  throwing. Replaced with a shape-inspecting `parse-invoke-id` helper
  (mirrors `parse-event-type`): only EDN-read shapes starting with `:`, `"`,
  `#`, or a digit/`-`; legacy bare strings pass through unchanged.
  Regression test: `legacy-invoke-id-decodes-as-string-test`.

2.0.4
-----

Six findings from the second deep review. Each has a regression test in
`persistence/jdbc/regression_test.clj` (findings #A–#F).

* **[P1]** `receive-events!` now re-sorts the claimed rows by
  `(deliver-at, id)` in memory before dispatching. PostgreSQL does not
  preserve the subquery's `ORDER BY` through `UPDATE … RETURNING *`, so a
  single poll that claimed multiple ready events for the same session
  could deliver them out of order. FIFO-per-session is restored.
* **[P1]** `receive-events!` is now session-aware when a handler fails:
  the failed event's claim is released AND any remaining events in that
  batch that target the SAME session are also released. Events for other
  sessions continue to process. This preserves per-session FIFO (the
  retried event must run before subsequent events for the same session)
  while keeping liveness for independent sessions (a poison event in one
  session can't block the queue).
* **[P2]** `queue-depth` with the `:session-id` filter now formats valid
  SQL. The previous `(update :where conj ...)` on `[:is :processed-at
  nil]` produced `[:is :processed-at nil [:= ...]]`, which HoneySQL
  formatted as `processed_at IS NULL IS (...)` — parse error at runtime.
* **[P2]** The durable-job worker's `dispatch-terminal-event!` now
  includes `:invoke-id` on the emitted event. Without it, the
  `InvocationProcessor` machinery (finalize, autoforward) couldn't match
  the event back to the originating `<invoke>` element.
* **[P2]** `DurableJobInvocationProcessor.start-invocation!` preserves
  namespaces on the stored `job_type`. Previously `(name src)` turned
  `:my.app/send-email` into `"send-email"`; the worker's handler lookup
  by `(keyword stored-job-type)` therefore missed the namespaced handler
  registration. Now stores the full keyword string via `(subs (str src) 1)`.
* **[P2]** The JDBC event queue now round-trips `:invoke-id` losslessly.
  `(name invoke-id)` threw on UUID/numeric invoke IDs and stripped
  namespaces from keyword IDs; both shapes are allowed by `::sc/id`.
  Storage now uses `(pr-str invoke-id)` and decode tries
  `edn/read-string` first, falling back to the raw DB string for legacy
  rows.

Housekeeping: the poison-event chaos test was rewritten to assert the
post-fix invariant correctly — a poison event on session A doesn't block
events on sessions B, C. The concurrent-session contention test bumped
retry limits to absorb contention now that optimistic locking actually
fires (follow-up from 2.0.2).

2.0.3
-----

Follow-ups from the post-2.0.2 review.

* **Async processor**: `v20150901_async_impl.cljc` had the same
  `(merge {defaults} wmem)` metadata-strip bug as the sync impl fixed in
  2.0.2. Users pairing the async processor with JDBC persistence (e.g.
  via `integration/fulcro`) still had optimistic locking silently
  disabled. Fixed by the same `with-meta (meta wmem)` wrapping in both
  `processing-env` and `process-event!`.
* **DurableJobInvocationProcessor** now honours the `InvocationProcessor`
  protocol when `create-job!` throws (e.g. exhausted race retries after
  2.0.2): returns `false` and emits an `:error.platform` event targeting
  the parent session, rather than letting the exception leak past the
  SCXML processor. Matches the pattern in `invocation/statechart.cljc`.

Regression coverage:
* `async-processing-env-preserves-wmem-metadata-test`
* `durable-job-start-invocation-survives-create-job-failure-test`

2.0.2
-----

Bug fixes surfaced by the deep review of the JDBC persistence layer. Each
fix has a regression test in
`persistence/jdbc/regression_test.clj`.

* **[CRITICAL]** Optimistic locking no longer silently disabled under
  `process-event!`. `with-processing-context` and `processing-env` in the
  SCXML algorithm preserved no metadata because `(merge {defaults} wmem)`
  inherits meta from the leftmost arg; the JDBC store's `::version` meta
  (attached by `fetch-session`) was therefore dropped on every event
  processing step, and `save-working-memory!` took the silent
  `ON CONFLICT DO UPDATE` branch. Fixed by re-attaching `(meta wmem)` after
  the defaults merge. Two nodes (or two worker threads) processing events
  for the same session concurrently now correctly surface an
  optimistic-lock failure on stale writers.
* `create-job!` no longer silently returns `nil` under adversarial races
  (INSERT-no-op → terminal transition → retry-INSERT-no-op). Retries up to
  5 times and throws `ex-info` with a clear message on exhaustion. Callers
  can no longer end up storing an empty-string job-id.
* `cancel!` and `cancel-by-session!` now write a terminal event
  (`error.invoke.<invokeid>` with data `{:reason :cancelled}`) so the
  reconciler can dispatch it to the parent session. Previously,
  cancelled-while-running jobs left parents wedged waiting for
  `done.invoke.X` / `error.invoke.X`.
* `get-undispatched-terminal-jobs` includes `cancelled` jobs (alongside
  `succeeded` and `failed`). The partial `idx_jobs_undispatched` index
  predicate widens to match; new DDL only — existing deployments keep
  their current index and queries still work (seq scan instead of index
  scan on cancelled jobs).
* `datasource-closed?` now falls back to a `getConnection` probe when the
  DataSource exposes no `isClosed` method. The event loop stops cleanly
  for plain `javax.sql.DataSource` instances (previously only worked for
  HikariCP).
* Event `:type` namespace preserved through queue round-trip. Storage
  changes from `(name type)` to `(pr-str type)`; decoder is
  backward-compatible (reads legacy un-namespaced values as unqualified
  keywords).
* Removed dead `insert-session!` in `working-memory-store.clj`; tightened
  the `upsert-session!` docstring.
* `send!`'s docstring spells out that the wake-signal is intra-JVM only.

2.0.1
-----

* `TIMESTAMPTZ → OffsetDateTime` conversion is now scoped to this library's
  queries via a `next.jdbc` `builder-adapter`, rather than a global
  `next.jdbc.result-set/ReadableColumn` extension. Fixes a conflict with
  consumers (notably Brian) that install their own `java.sql.Timestamp`
  extensions on the same JVM.
* Added an integration test asserting `TIMESTAMPTZ` columns from lib queries
  come back as `OffsetDateTime`.

2.0.0
-----

BREAKING: The PostgreSQL persistence layer was migrated from pg2 to next.jdbc.

* Dropped `com.github.igrishaev/pg2-honey` (pg2); added `com.github.seancorfield/next.jdbc`,
  `com.github.seancorfield/honeysql`, and `org.postgresql/postgresql` as direct deps.
* Renamed the namespace segment `com.fulcrologic.statecharts.persistence.pg.*` to
  `com.fulcrologic.statecharts.persistence.jdbc.*`. Update your imports accordingly.
* Constructors now accept a `javax.sql.DataSource` instead of a pg2 pool:
    * `persistence.jdbc/pg-env` takes `:datasource` instead of `:pool`.
    * `persistence.jdbc.working-memory-store/new-store`, `event-queue/new-queue`,
      `registry/new-registry` all take a DataSource.
    * HikariCP is the standard choice; any DataSource that `next.jdbc` accepts
      will work.
* Record names renamed: `PostgresWorkingMemoryStore` → `JdbcWorkingMemoryStore`,
  `PostgresEventQueue` → `JdbcEventQueue`, `PostgresStatechartRegistry` →
  `JdbcStatechartRegistry`. The record field holding the DataSource is
  `:datasource` (was `:pool`).
* Schema, SQL semantics, and Nippy wire format are unchanged. Tables, columns,
  indexes, `SELECT FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED`, `ON CONFLICT` upserts, and BYTEA
  round-trips all behave identically.
* `TIMESTAMPTZ` reads are returned as `java.time.OffsetDateTime` (matching the
  prior pg2 backend); pgjdbc's default `java.sql.Timestamp` is adapted in
  `persistence.jdbc.core`.

1.1.6
-----

Fulcro integration tuning:

* Reduced logging noise
* Added 4-arity version in the lambda execution model, so event-name and event-data are available in expressions as args 3 and 4 respectively.
* Changed Fulcro integration to use the 4-arg version of lambda (default is still 2-arg in non-Fulcro, for bw compat in CLJ)
* Added auto-expansion of fulcro aliases into the `data` arg (2) of the expressions, again for convenience. A warning will show in dev time if there are conflicts on keys.

